title: Seidel: MSU drops to 6th, U-M slides up to 17th

(Photo: Mitch Stringer, USA TODAY Sports) 6 CONNECT 9 TWEET LINKEDIN 12 COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
This was a weekend of slips and failures, upsets and escapes – just bring your own guts. 
Four teams in the top 10 went down. 
Ohio State still hasn’t reached its potential, but the Buckeyes escaped against Indiana (4-1). 
Michigan State was nearly upset against Purdue and those injuries keep piling up for the Spartans. 
As far as Michigan, the Wolverines have a stingy, nasty defense that posted its second-straight shutout. 
So let’s get right to it. 
Ohio State stays No.1 on my Associated Press top 25 ballot. 
Michigan State drops. 
Michigan is on the climb again. 
And holy Toledo – the Rockets break into my top 25. 
Before I get a ton of emails from MSU fans full of outrage about why I’m dropping MSU (two spots on my ballot) to No.6 after a close win, but I am not dropping Ohio State after a close win against a 4-1 team, let me be clear. Ohio State has more talent than MSU. Ohio State is the defending national champion. The Buckeyes have a ton of players back from that team and have won 18 straight games. 
Right now, MSU’s offensive line is banged up and its defense is nowhere near what was expected. This week, MSU improved its pass defense, and now, the run defense is leaky. 
I’m also putting Utah above MSU, and I admit that’s a week late. MSU hung on to beat Oregon at home. Utah crushed Oregon on the road. And then MSU barely got past Purdue. Meanwhile, every day, Utah’s victory over Michigan looks more impressive for the Utes. 
TCU is my new No.2 ranked team, after four straight games of putting up 50 or more points. 
Baylor moves up because the Bears are doing something that MSU has not been able to do: The Bears are crushing the teams they should crush. Baylor’s average victory margin is somewhere near ridiculous. 
Clemson moves up after a two-point win over Notre Dame. The guess here is that Clemson will beat Florida State at home on Nov.7 and be one of the last four teams standing. 
And I’m keeping Ole Miss in my top 25, based on its victory over Alabama. I know you could make an argument that Ole Miss should be ranked ahead of Alabama – based on head to head matchup – but not after the way Ole Miss played on Saturday and Alabama bounced back. 
Also, Iowa, which is off to its best start since 2009, cracks my top 25 with a 10-6 victory over No.19 Wisconsin. 
That gives the Big 10 five teams in my top 25. 
Jeff Seidel’s top 25 
1. Ohio State
